metadata.title: Stinson 108
aws::graph::propositions: 1508 Stinson 108 aircraft were built between 1947 and 1948.
Stinson 108-2 is powered by a 165 hp (123 kW) Franklin 6A4-165-B3 engine.
Stinson 108-2 is powered by a 165 hp (123 kW) Franklin 6A4-165-B5 engine.
1250 Stinson 108-2 aircraft were built from May 1948.
A conversion kit was advertised to add rudder trim to earlier Stinson 108 airplanes.
Stinson 108-3 introduced a taller vertical fin with a rudder featuring a straight trailing edge.
Stinson 108-3 was fitted with larger fuel tanks of 50 U.S. gallons (190 L; 42 imp gal).
Earlier Stinson 108 models had fuel tanks of 40 U.S. gallons (150 L; 33 imp gal).
Stinson 108-3 has a higher gross weight of 2,400 lb (1,089 kg) than its predecessors.
1760 Stinson 108-3 aircraft were built by Stinson and Piper.
Stinson 108-4 is a higher powered model of the Stinson 108.
Stinson 108-4 was flown experimentally by Stinson.
Stinson 108-4 was later flown by Piper.

108-2
Powered by 165 hp (123 kW) Franklin 6A4-165-B3 or -B5. 1250 built from May 1948. There was a conversion kit to add the rudder trim to the earlier airplanes advertised.

108-3
The 108-3 introduced a taller vertical fin with a rudder featuring a straight trailing edge. Larger fuel tanks (50 U.S. gallons (190 L; 42 imp gal) versus 40 U.S. gallons (150 L; 33 imp gal)) were also fitted. The -3 has a higher gross weight than its predecessors of 2,400 lb (1,089 kg). 1760 built by Stinson and Piper.
108-4
The 108-4 is a higher powered model 108, sn 108-4693, NX149C, not certified, flown experimentally by Stinson, later by Piper, 1 built.
